node.text: This is the most tragic thing I’ve ever filmed: a pod of dolphins swimming through a giant oil spill. The spill is spanning an area covering more than 50 miles, and it is lurking just off the coast of San Diego. On today’s extended trip we made our way to our reliable Blue Whale hotspot near San Clemente Island and we were shocked when the whales seemingly vanished. Just 24 hours earlier this zone was full of the feeding giants. It was then that we began making our way south, and soon made this shocking discovery. Tragic doesn’t begin to cover it. For more than 50 miles the ocean was covered in a thick sheen of oil, a devastating tragedy for the environment. We know very little at this time, and we are trying to make these images go viral in hopes of getting some answers as to how this happened. More shocking yet, 70+ miles away back in coastal San Diego, the local whale watching boats reported an area thick with oil encroaching on the local waters as well. I truly hope this isn’t as bad as it appears, but if this oil is already in an area that spans at a minimum of 70 miles, we could have a catastrophe of unimaginable scale on our hands. Please share this video with your followers and tag people, celebrities, influencers and news media that need to see and share it too: WE NEED ANSWERS BEFORE ANY MORE MARINE LIFE SUFFERS! We’ve reached out to NOAA, the Coast Guard, and the EPA. We hope to have an update soon. Video and caption by our friend @dolphindronedom #saveouroceans

PLEASE TAKE ACTION NOW! A seemingly small action today really will help make a historical change to HELP SAVE SHARKS in Hawaii! We’ve been pretty quiet about this on social media til this point but it is now the FINAL step to getting sharks fully protected in Hawaii! 

Please lend them your voice by writing into to the Governor of Hawaii today via the link in the bio @oneoceanconservation and ask him to : “PROTECT SHARKS by please SUPPORTING and signing HB553 into law.”

The link is in the bio of @oneoceanconservation 

and I have a good feeling this is the year that manō (sharks) in Hawaii get the protection that they need, deserve, and traditionally were given. Lets protect sharks everywhere we can and for me it’s significant to see the manō I have grown up with (who have taught me so much) get protection from purposeful killing, capture, entanglement, and harm. 

Video of Roxy, I’m grateful she seems to visit me around my birthday, the holidays, and when she needs debris like this net and fishing line removed. This law will help to reduce nets in shark nursery habitats (nets like the ones we’ve cut off her several times) and hopefully save other sharks from broken jaws like hers as it will be a fineable offense to purposely (not accidentally) capture or kill a shark. This law won’t criminalize accidental capture, but it will mean that fisherman must let a shark go if they realize they do accidentally capture a shark, which responsible fishermen already do. 

LINK IN BIO @OneOceanConservation PLEASE SUPPORT THE PROTECTION OF SHARKS TODAY. Mahalo nui loa. Malamamano Respect and protect sharks. 
Special thanks to the many organizations, individuals, reps, and senators who have been helping support this bill all along the way and for many years now. #ForManō #HelpSaveSharks #protectsharks #SaveTheOcean

Please take a moment to help stop this by signing the petition in @oceancreature23’s bio ‼️This happened yesterday in Fish Head Ari Atoll, one of the most popular dive sites in the Maldives. And now the government opened discussions to legalize shark fishing. Shark fishing was banned since 2010 after the shark population was destroyed almost to the point of no return. Only recently sharks have started to come back to some areas and if they allow it to happen again sharks will be gone in just a matter of few months. Lets pressure the government to stop this. Pls tag these accounts and share as much as you can.... @presidentmohamednasheed 
@presidencymv @epamaldives 
@mofmramv 
.
.
Video by @pauwels.thomas 
Shark fin photos by Maldives Customs

node.text:
Happy international women’s day / Thank you @pelagicdivefuvahmulah for inviting me to your tiger shark island #paradise and this was so exciting to be a part of taking the first local woman from #fuvamulah island to snorkel with tiger sharks out in the #pelagic deep open ocean. We have a new #LadyShark 💕🦈💕 I have always actively supported women in science, conservation, environmental causes, and diving is such a great way to inspire that for men and women alike, not to mention it’s good for your physical and mental well-being 💙 Thank you to @pelagicdivefuvahmulah for empowering women and facilitating programs in the local and international community and thank you to my new Seaster featured here: @anshooda 💞🥰 for volunteering, she says life on land is boring in comparison to this 💕🦈💕 This was her first time snorkeling and first time seeing a shark.
#InternationalWomensDay #StrongWomen #Seasters #LadySharks 

Filmed by my love: @juansharks 😘
#Maldives @oneoceanglobal #beautifulmaldives #womendiving #womenwhodive

I have come to love filming Great White Sharks
They are so mysterious, beautiful and a great challenge to film.
This 3m male has a lot of scrape marks all over him, there are some thoughts on what may be causing this but no one really knows. I would be very curiuous to learn more. Filmed at The Neptune Islands South Australia with Rodney Fox Shark Expeditions.

Words by @sharkgirlmadison -
I feel incredibly lucky to have encountered every species of shark in this frame in the wild. Although it makes filming a scene like this even more heart wrenching for me. Take a close look at these sharks, six different species, two are critically endangered. They are less than half of the total catch of one shark fishing boat from Indonesia. This exact same boat is set to turn around in 3 weeks and go back to sea again to fish sharks. When you examine why you realise the captain has a 15 year old son who's studying away from home so he can have a better future than fishing. That's his motivation to go back to sea. Few times do I get to boast about wins in these dark times, so I'm going to do that now. We've paid for his sons tuition this month. Then as part of @projecthiu I will be hiring his boat to scout new tourism locations for the next two months. The boat is NOT turning around to fish sharks. It will stay here and the captain and his crew will return to their families each night instead of going back out to sea. Their income will increase by 503% and the damage they do on the high seas will not be done. Last week I stood amongst the dead sharks from their haul, tomorrow I free dive off their boat, with the knowledge that for a short span of time we were able to improve someone life above, and some life's below. This was made possible by every single one of you that's supported @projecthiu and the following individuals that made it possible for me to be here @caraghcreative @3enhall @convowithryan @bryndabella @sunbutterskincare it's a small win for the situation at hand, when filming this becomes your norm, you need the small wins.

X MAN OF THE SEA X
Via @zimydakid 

*** FULL FILM ON YT ***

Man of the Sea tells the story of @pierrick_moana, a tahitian freediver that has dedicated his entire life to the ocean and the protection of sharks.

From the migrating Humpback Whales, to the huge Tiger Sharks as well as the importance of having a healthy ocean, this short film will take you on a journey to discover the deepest parts of French Polynesia and learn more about the true heart and soul of these magical islands, lost in the South Pacific Ocean.

Make sure to have a look at the full film on my YT channel (link in @zimydakid’s bio) !

Film shot (only freediving) and edited by myself, starring @pierrick_moana, in association with @maomanafoundation 

Big thanks to everyone that helped make this come to life: @captchewy, Gael, Teddy, @manateacouraud, @kokocuvier, @immadiscoveler, Taurama, Kamalei & Kailani, @mooreamoanatours

Via @silenthunter_pty Mrs. @silenthunter_pty @bolton_becky was so stoked when she captured this Juvenile Great White in a full out of water breach!! 🎥🦈. This is vary rare at #guadalupeisland and is also rare for a breaching juvenile .. Her persistence , determination and waiting out for the perfect clip was rewarded on this day.. bravo soulmate !! I am sure she will capture more good great white shots during our 2021 expeditions .
@oceanramsey @juansharks @dickie_chivell @shrkba8 @apexsurvival @marks.clark @silenthunter_pty @lizparkinson1 @feroab #greatwhiteshark #guadalupeisland @abc4explore @forrest.galante @deanocook @emily_r_king

node.text: By @tannerunderwater This morning was a dream. This Scalloped Hammerhead was at our fin tips the entire dive, weaving between our guests and checking us out for over an hour before we had to pack up and take off. Days like this I always reflect on how truly, truly lucky I feel to spend my days in the ocean. I believe I have already lived a full life, experienced more than most would in multiple lifetimes and it’s all because of days like this. Feelings like this.. life doesn’t get much better. The ocean is my home. It’s where I am at peace.

node.text:
MALDIVES SHARK EXPEDITION🚨 
We are beyond excited to announce the launch of our first MALDIVES expeditions! In collaboration with @pelagicdivefuvamulah

You will be fully accommodated with 3 Dives per day to encounter Tresher Sharks, Tiger Sharks, Whale Sharks and Mantas, food and Non Alcoholic drinks, photos and videos of the trip taken by the @discoversharks team, @tannerunderwater @alexsharks_ @jalilnajafov @janelleunderwater also your participation will support local businesses and ocean conservation organizations! The expedition will be broadcast live on @discoversharks 🎥
 CLICK THE LINK IN BIO or 📧: DM your email address to @discoversharkstours to get more details and  book your spot ! 

Save the date! 
September 1st - 8th 2021 

📷 @pelagicdivefuvahmulah

Warning - graphic content.
If this video breaks your heart too, sign the petition at the link in @shawnheinrichs’s bio to stop the killing of sharks in Costa Rica. ⁠
⁠
Costa Rica has more than 40 species of sharks, and almost half are in serious danger of extinction, including silky sharks and hammerhead sharks. Costa Rica, a country that prides itself on protecting its endangered marine wildlife, is doing an abysmal job of stemming the alarming decline of endangered shark species in its waters.⁠ 
⁠
Earlier this year, Costa Rica’s government essentially legalized the overfishing, and subsequent extinction, of endangered sharks. President @carlosalvq removed the ability of the Ministry of Environment to protect sharks, and shifted management responsibilities to the Institute of Fisheries and Aquaculture (INCOPESCA) – meaning they are no longer protected by Costa Rica’s Wildlife Conservation Law.⁠ Sign the petition at the link in @shawnheinrichs’s bio and share this post to help spread the word. Today, we are asking President Alvarado to immediately repeal his harmful executive decree and restore the Ministry of Environment’s authority to conserve and protect sharks. 
⁠
Video by @Shawnheinrichs, @Andy_Mann⁠, and @paulnicklen
Conservation leadership by @randall_arauz @carola_ramirezcr @migramarnet @finsattached

Words by @_bugdreamer_ 🦈🦈 Meet Scabby!! My favourite Sand Tiger shark⠀
⠀
One of the best experiences I‘ve had while scuba diving.⠀⠀
Despite their “scary” looks, size and intimidating teeth, I learned that Sand tiger sharks are incredibly docile and absolutely not a threat to humans.⠀⠀
It is pretty hard to describe how it feels when a large creature like this makes eye contact with you! Immediately my heart accelerated and I started using the air from my tank real fast ... but the shark didn’t seem to mind my presence. He was totally chill as if I wasn’t even there.⠀⠀
I relaxed, turned my camera on and filmed Scabby from every single angle I could’ve asked for!!⠀⠀
Some people unfortunately label sharks as dangerous and killers when reality is that they are simply peaceful, curious animals 😍⠀
